Yeah, she's my Buck Rogers ship.

926
01:13:19.815 --> 01:13:21.816
She's a looker.

927
01:13:22.484 --> 01:13:24.110
Okay, what do you got for me?

928
01:13:31.535 --> 01:13:33.786
Jiminy Cricket.

929
01:13:33.954 --> 01:13:37.623
Seating capacity for 60.
Wingspan, 123 feet.


930
01:13:37.791 --> 01:13:41.168
Four Double Cyclone engines.
Her ceiling's 25,000 feet.


931
01:13:41.336 --> 01:13:44.547
- Gross weight?
- 86,000, wing loading of 41 pounds.


932
01:13:44.715 --> 01:13:47.508
So less drag on
the plane in thinner air.

933
01:13:47.676 --> 01:13:51.178
So high-cruise power, you're looking
at a top speed of around 340.


934
01:13:52.222 --> 01:13:55.808
Giving her a range of about 3000 miles.

935
01:13:56.977 --> 01:13:59.478
- Cross-country.
- Non-stop.


936
01:14:00.772 --> 01:14:02.356
Bob ...

937
01:14:02.524 --> 01:14:05.693
... you know something?
You are a son of a bitch.


938
01:14:16.622 --> 01:14:20.124
Yeah. Bob, you got
something on your suit.


939
01:14:21.710 --> 01:14:23.169
Yeah.

940
01:14:23.545 --> 01:14:26.047
On your lapel.
You got something on your lapel.


941
01:14:29.176 --> 01:14:31.052
Right there, Bob.

942
01:14:32.804 --> 01:14:34.388
You missed it. Right there.

943
01:14:36.683 --> 01:14:38.559
Clean it off, would you?

944
01:14:38.727 --> 01:14:41.228
Here. Thanks.

945
01:14:44.483 --> 01:14:45.900
No, throw it away.

946
01:14:49.946 --> 01:14:51.364
No, over there.

947
01:14:57.871 --> 01:15:01.707
Thanks. So, what do you call her?

948
01:15:01.875 --> 01:15:04.043
The Constellation,
but we can change that.


949
01:15:04.211 --> 01:15:05.836
No, no.

950
01:15:06.004 --> 01:15:09.048
It's pretty. I like her.

951
01:15:10.008 --> 01:15:12.093
So, what kind of
deal can you give me?

952
01:15:12.260 --> 01:15:14.095
What kind of deal can you give me?

953
01:15:14.262 --> 01:15:16.555
The first 40 planes off the assembly line.

954
01:15:16.723 --> 01:15:19.266
That should give us about
two years' exclusivity.


955
01:15:19.434 --> 01:15:20.726
Hell, more than that.

956
01:15:20.894 --> 01:15:24.897
United and American don't have
the imagination for a plane like this.


957
01:15:25.065 --> 01:15:27.650
Two years ahead of Juan Trippe, then.

958
01:15:32.698 --> 01:15:33.948
How much?

959
01:15:34.116 --> 01:15:36.283
Four hundred and fifty thousand each.

960
01:15:37.119 --> 01:15:39.954
So that's 18 million for the first 40.

961
01:15:40.914 --> 01:15:43.958
Hell, TWA can't afford that.
The damn airline's flat broke.


962
01:15:48.130 --> 01:15:50.631
Guess I'll just have
to pay for them myself.


963
01:15:51.508 --> 01:15:54.593
Build them, Bob.
Send the bill to Noah Dietrich.


964
01:15:54.761 --> 01:15:56.303
Oh, and thank you.

965
01:16:00.058 --> 01:16:01.892
Merry Christmas.

966
01:16:02.060 --> 01:16:06.522
You've just placed the largest order for
airplanes in the history of the damn planet.


967
01:16:06.690 --> 01:16:08.816
Lockheed sent us a bill for $18 million.

968
01:16:08.984 --> 01:16:12.278
Don't get all hysterical on me, Noah.
It isn't good for you.


969
01:16:12.446 --> 01:16:15.781
- This is a lot of money for planes.
- I know it's a lot of money.


970
01:16:15.949 --> 01:16:19.577
It's too damn much. You think I've got
$18 million in petty cash?


971
01:16:19.745 --> 01:16:21.912
I should've told you. 
It slipped my mind.

972
01:16:22.080 --> 01:16:23.998
- Slipped your mind? Oh, for --
- Right.


973
01:16:24.166 --> 01:16:27.626
- I'll get back to you. Bye.
- How could $18 million slip your mind?


974
01:16:28.503 --> 01:16:31.672
Hey, honey.
What are you doing home?


975
01:16:36.094 --> 01:16:38.929
You're not one for tears, and, well ...

976
01:16:39.097 --> 01:16:43.350
... neither am l,
so it's best to come out with it.


977
01:16:46.480 --> 01:16:50.691
I've met someone.
I've fallen in love and I'm moving out.


978
01:16:53.320 --> 01:16:58.073
If I could make it
any more gentle, I would.


979
01:16:58.241 --> 01:17:02.328
But I can't, so ...

980
01:17:03.371 --> 01:17:05.247
... there we both are.

981
01:17:08.877 --> 01:17:10.711
Let's be honest.

982
01:17:10.879 --> 01:17:15.382
It's all been a grand adventure,
but it couldn't possibly last.


983
01:17:15.550 --> 01:17:18.427
We're too alike, you and I.

984
01:17:21.556 --> 01:17:22.890
You met someone?

985
01:17:23.058 --> 01:17:26.977
Someone more appropriate.
To me, I mean.


986
01:17:29.689 --> 01:17:32.650
What does that mean,
"more appropriate"?


987
01:17:33.068 --> 01:17:37.154
Someone more attuned to my needs.

988
01:17:37.697 --> 01:17:39.615
Look at me, Katie.

989
01:17:39.783 --> 01:17:41.700
Stop acting.

990
01:17:42.118 --> 01:17:44.912
I'm not acting.

991
01:17:49.543 --> 01:17:52.169
I wonder if you even know anymore.

992
01:17:57.092 --> 01:17:59.301
Don't be unkind.

993
01:18:02.013 --> 01:18:03.722
You ...?

994
01:18:05.058 --> 01:18:06.392
You wanna go?

995
01:18:10.021 --> 01:18:11.647
Go on.

996
01:18:12.232 --> 01:18:15.359
Actresses are cheap in this town, darling.

997
01:18:15.527 --> 01:18:18.112
- And I got a lot of money.
- This is beneath you.


998
01:18:18.280 --> 01:18:20.739
No, no, this is exactly me.

999
01:18:20.907 --> 01:18:26.036
You tell me you're leaving me, and you
have the nerve to expect graciousness?


1000
01:18:26.496 --> 01:18:28.497
I expect a little maturity.

1001
01:18:28.665 --> 01:18:31.584
I expect you to face the situation
like an adult who --


1002
01:18:31.751 --> 01:18:34.044
Don't talk down to me!

1003
01:18:34.212 --> 01:18:37.214
Don't you ever talk down to me!
You are a movie star.


1004
01:18:37.382 --> 01:18:38.966
Nothing more.

1005
01:19:50.997 --> 01:19:52.915
Don't answer it.

1006
01:19:55.794 --> 01:19:57.503
What is it, Howard?

1007
01:19:57.671 --> 01:19:59.964
Hey, Noah ...

1008
01:20:00.131 --> 01:20:03.133
... I need you to get to Penney's
and buy me some clothes.


1009
01:20:03.301 --> 01:20:05.094
- Penney's isn't open.
- Oh, shit.


1010
01:20:05.261 --> 01:20:08.222
- It's 2 in the morning.
- Yeah, that's right.


1011
01:20:08.390 --> 01:20:11.100
Well, first thing tomorrow, then, all right?

1012
01:20:11.267 --> 01:20:14.353
I need two new suits off the rack.
One light and one dark.


1013
01:20:14.521 --> 01:20:17.731
Three white shirts and three pairs
of white tennis shoes. Got that?


1014
01:20:17.899 --> 01:20:19.858
- Yeah.
- No, no.


1015
01:20:20.026 --> 01:20:21.860
- Make it Woolworth's.
- Woolworth's.


1016
01:20:22.028 --> 01:20:24.613
No, no, Penney's. Penney's.

1017
01:20:24.781 --> 01:20:26.532
All right.

1018
01:20:27.242 --> 01:20:30.035
I'll get into it as
soon as I can, Howard.

1019
01:20:30.370 --> 01:20:32.913
- All right?
- Noah, do you have a recorder?


1020
01:20:33.623 --> 01:20:36.834
- No.
- Are you recording this conversation?


1021
01:20:37.002 --> 01:20:39.420
- No.
- Okay.


1022
01:20:39.587 --> 01:20:41.422
I trust you.

1023
01:20:42.424 --> 01:20:45.801
- Howard --
- I need those suits first thing tomorrow.


1024
01:20:45.969 --> 01:20:49.430
- All right.
- Wait. Did I say Penney's or Woolworth's?


1025
01:20:49.597 --> 01:20:52.266
- Penney's.
- Better make it Sears.


1026
01:20:52.434 --> 01:20:54.935
All right, then, Sears.

1027
01:20:57.772 --> 01:20:59.940
I'm sorry, honey.

1028
01:21:01.151 --> 01:21:03.444
If I don't answer, he'll just call back.

1029
01:21:25.300 --> 01:21:28.343
Stop there, if you please, 
Miss Domergue.

1030
01:21:34.225 --> 01:21:36.143
Have you had surgery, 
Miss Domergue?

1031
01:21:37.979 --> 01:21:39.480
No.

1032
01:21:40.315 --> 01:21:43.400
Do you have scars of any kind?

1033
01:21:44.819 --> 01:21:46.320
No.

1034
01:21:47.989 --> 01:21:50.115
Wipe off your lipstick.

1035
01:21:54.662 --> 01:21:55.954
That's much better.

1036
01:21:57.540 --> 01:22:02.461
Now, you understand that you'd be
under contract to me? Personally.


1037
01:22:03.379 --> 01:22:05.005
Do you know what that means?

1038
01:22:13.848 --> 01:22:15.641
Now turn around for me.

1039
01:22:23.900 --> 01:22:25.400
Very nice.

1040
01:22:26.528 --> 01:22:28.403
You move well.

1041
01:22:31.241 --> 01:22:33.200
You live with your family, do you?

1042
01:22:35.328 --> 01:22:36.912
Yes.

1043
01:22:37.372 --> 01:22:38.914
That's nice.

1044
01:22:40.250 --> 01:22:42.042
Tell me something.

1045
01:22:43.378 --> 01:22:45.796
How old are you, 
Miss Domergue?

1046
01:22:48.758 --> 01:22:50.551
Fifteen.

1047
01:22:53.930 --> 01:22:55.097
Holy Mother of God.

1048
01:23:14.534 --> 01:23:18.328
Well, a car picks me up
every morning at 8, and off I go.


1049
01:23:18.496 --> 01:23:21.540
I'm getting my high school diploma.

1050
01:23:21.708 --> 01:23:24.418
Howard thinks that education is important.

1051
01:23:24.586 --> 01:23:26.962
- That's right.
- And then, after classes ...


1052
01:23:27.130 --> 01:23:30.716
... I'm off for elocution
and grooming and fittings.


1053
01:23:30.884 --> 01:23:32.676
Well, blow me down.

1054
01:23:33.887 --> 01:23:36.096
Pan Am's working
out of the Cocoanut Grove?


1055
01:23:36.264 --> 01:23:38.223
- Hello, Jack.
- Hello, Juan.


1056
01:23:38.391 --> 01:23:40.100
Helen, good to see you.

1057
01:23:40.268 --> 01:23:42.769
- How are you, Howard?
- Good, thanks.


1058
01:23:42.937 --> 01:23:44.771
- This is Faith Domergue.
- Sit down.


1059
01:23:44.939 --> 01:23:46.773
- Pleasure.
- What are you doing here?


1060
01:23:46.941 --> 01:23:49.776
Well, I'm out to meet
with Douglas about the DC-4.


1061
01:23:49.944 --> 01:23:53.780
It's our new plane, and it is
gonna be a pip, let me tell you.


1062
01:23:53.948 --> 01:23:57.159
- How's the Constellation coming?
- Good.


1063
01:23:57.452 --> 01:23:58.744
Great.

1064
01:24:00.121 --> 01:24:02.623
So how about letting me steal a peek?

1065
01:24:04.626 --> 01:24:06.585
I don't think so.

1066
01:24:06.753 --> 01:24:09.796
I should be cross with you.
You stole Ray Loewy from us.


1067
01:24:10.590 --> 01:24:14.134
- He's doing our interior design. That's right.
- He was doing ours.


1068
01:24:16.638 --> 01:24:18.388
So ...

1069
01:24:18.932 --> 01:24:21.391
... what are your colors?
- Stop fishing.


1070
01:24:23.144 --> 01:24:25.646
So you have buttons ...

1071
01:24:25.813 --> 01:24:27.231
... or zippers?

1072
01:24:27.649 --> 01:24:28.941
I'm sorry?

1073
01:24:30.860 --> 01:24:34.780
Buttons or zippers for the drapes
on the sleeping berths?


1074
01:24:38.284 --> 01:24:39.952
Zippers.

1075
01:24:48.836 --> 01:24:50.420
Buttons.

1076
01:25:00.098 --> 01:25:03.100
So I suppose you'll be
expanding on down to Mexico.


1077
01:25:03.601 --> 01:25:07.145
- Why do you say that?
- Well, your range is 3000 miles.


1078
01:25:07.313 --> 01:25:11.400
I'd imagine you'd expand from Los Angeles
to Mexico and South America.


1079
01:25:11.567 --> 01:25:13.735
Hey, that's a good idea.
Anyone got a pen?


1080
01:25:13.903 --> 01:25:16.029
Or across the Atlantic.

1081
01:25:19.033 --> 01:25:20.951
You've had enough of this ice cream.

1082
01:25:21.119 --> 01:25:24.705
You give me that spoon. You don't
wanna get your gloves all sticky.


1083
01:25:26.666 --> 01:25:28.542
Isn't that too far?

1084
01:25:33.548 --> 01:25:35.465
New York ...

1085
01:25:35.633 --> 01:25:37.676
... to Newfoundland ...

1086
01:25:38.386 --> 01:25:39.636
... to Ireland.

1087
01:25:44.892 --> 01:25:46.476
To Paris.

1088
01:25:53.609 --> 01:25:55.235
Well ...

1089
01:25:55.778 --> 01:25:57.904
... Pan Am welcomes you.

1090
01:25:58.072 --> 01:25:59.906
We're overbooked as it is.

1091
01:26:00.074 --> 01:26:03.702
It's such a burden doing it all
on your own, let me tell you.


1092
01:26:03.870 --> 01:26:05.912
So when's the Connie gonna be ready?

1093
01:26:06.080 --> 01:26:08.749
- Next year maybe. DC-4?
- Next year.


1094
01:26:08.916 --> 01:26:12.085
Well, we look forward to her then.

1095
01:26:12.628 --> 01:26:14.379
And I to the Connie.

1096
01:26:16.257 --> 01:26:19.885
I've ordered the next 40 after you.

1097
01:26:20.094 --> 01:26:21.887
- It's Miss ...?
- Domergue.


1098
01:26:22.055 --> 01:26:25.432
Yes, of course. Now, was that a
rumba or a samba you were doing?


1099
01:26:25.850 --> 01:26:28.602
- I' was a samba.
- A samba, yes.


1100
01:26:28.770 --> 01:26:32.022
Howard, I never knew
you were such a good dancer.


1101
01:26:32.982 --> 01:26:34.816
Helen, Jack.

1102
01:26:36.652 --> 01:26:39.446
Good going. You gave away
our entire postwar strategy.


1103
01:26:39.614 --> 01:26:44.117
- He can't stop us.
- He's Pan Am. He can stop anything.


1104
01:26:46.120 --> 01:26:47.954
Give me the largest
Scotch you got.


1105
01:26:48.122 --> 01:26:51.708
I don't know what in the hell you're
so damn giddy about. Excuse me.


1106
01:28:43.779 --> 01:28:45.238
Jack.

1107
01:28:45.406 --> 01:28:49.034
Get in touch with Joyce and Berg.
Those are my boys in Washington.


1108
01:28:49.202 --> 01:28:52.579
Set up a meeting with Jones,
secretary of commerce, old golfing buddy.


1109
01:28:52.747 --> 01:28:55.707
- Slow down.
- We'll need terminals in Ireland and France.


1110
01:28:55.875 --> 01:28:57.334
I wanna get some tax breaks.

1111
01:28:57.502 --> 01:29:01.171
If that ass thinks he owns the world,
he's got another thing coming.


1112
01:29:01.339 --> 01:29:04.216
Pan Am owns Europe.
We ought to think about Mexico.


1113
01:29:04.383 --> 01:29:08.470
To hell with Mexico. No airline should
have a monopoly on flying the Atlantic.


1114
01:29:08.638 --> 01:29:11.932
It just isn't fair.
He owns Pan Am, he owns Congress.


1115
01:29:12.099 --> 01:29:15.936
He owns the Civil Aeronautics Board,
but he does not own the sky.


1116
01:29:16.103 --> 01:29:18.772
We're in a street fight
with that son of a bitch.


1117
01:29:18.940 --> 01:29:22.609
I've been fighting high-hat
Ivy League pricks like him my whole life.


1118
01:29:22.777 --> 01:29:26.404
And listen, fire Ray Loewy.
You goddamn heard me? Fire Ray Loewy.


1119
01:29:26.572 --> 01:29:29.950
He's spying for Trippe.
That shitheel knew all about the buttons.


1120
01:29:30.117 --> 01:29:32.118
Spies in my midst, Jack.

1121
01:29:32.787 --> 01:29:34.621
Spies in my midst.

1122
01:29:49.053 --> 01:29:51.972
- Hello, Howard.
- Roland.


1123
01:29:53.849 --> 01:29:55.433
So ...

1124
01:29:55.601 --> 01:29:57.143
... what can I do for you?

1125
01:30:00.314 --> 01:30:04.317
I want all the pictures you have
of Kate Hepburn and Spencer Tracy.


1126
01:30:04.485 --> 01:30:08.029
All the negatives.
And I want you to kill the story.


1127
01:30:08.197 --> 01:30:11.575
Howard, he's a married man.
He's a Catholic.


1128
01:30:11.742 --> 01:30:13.994
They're movie stars.
Fair game all around.


1129
01:30:22.503 --> 01:30:24.671
My office knows where I am, Howard.

1130
01:30:25.673 --> 01:30:28.508
I'm not gonna kill you, Roland.

1131
01:30:28.676 --> 01:30:30.594
I don't do that.

1132
01:30:35.349 --> 01:30:37.976
- How much?
- Not for sale.


1133
01:30:41.230 --> 01:30:42.814
How much?

1134
01:30:43.691 --> 01:30:46.860
Not for sale.

1135
01:30:50.197 --> 01:30:52.282
You ever cheat on your wife, Roland?

1136
01:30:54.076 --> 01:30:56.536
You ever screw a colored girl?

1137
01:30:57.204 --> 01:31:00.373
You ever steal anything?
You ever hurt anyone?


1138
01:31:02.543 --> 01:31:04.377
Good night, Howard.

1139
01:31:04.754 --> 01:31:07.714
You ever go to
a Communist Party meeting, Roland?


1140
01:31:17.558 --> 01:31:19.726
TWA stock.

1141
01:31:20.728 --> 01:31:22.020
How much?

1142
01:31:23.606 --> 01:31:25.065
Fifty thousand shares.

1143
01:31:25.733 --> 01:31:27.192
Ten.

1144
01:31:30.237 --> 01:31:31.571
All right.

1145
01:31:34.700 --> 01:31:36.534
This isn't gonna be that easy.

1146
01:31:36.911 --> 01:31:40.288
He's been making big contributions
on both sides of the aisle.


1147
01:31:40.456 --> 01:31:43.917
And Jack Frye is out there
lobbying everybody in town.


1148
01:31:44.085 --> 01:31:47.253
The French and British ambassadors
are lined up on his side.


1149
01:31:48.589 --> 01:31:51.758
I'm telling you, TWA is serious
about going international.


1150
01:31:51.926 --> 01:31:53.551
Okay.

1151
01:31:53.719 --> 01:31:55.637
Point, Mr. Hughes.

1152
01:31:56.013 --> 01:31:59.683
I think it's time for you to introduce
the community airline bill ...


1153
01:31:59.850 --> 01:32:01.393
... on the floor of the Senate.

1154
01:32:02.395 --> 01:32:05.188
- Is it done?
- My people are finishing it right now.


1155
01:32:05.356 --> 01:32:09.901
I also have to get you on the committee
investigating the national defense.


1156
01:32:12.321 --> 01:32:15.407
On the committee or chairman?

1157
01:32:15.741 --> 01:32:18.410
I could be much more effective
as chairman.


1158
01:32:18.577 --> 01:32:22.330
It's a great public platform.
You know, it generates a lot of press.


1159
01:32:22.498 --> 01:32:25.959
- Wasn't Truman chairman of that committee?
- Yeah, right.


1160
01:32:26.127 --> 01:32:28.545
He's vice president.
Look what he did with it.


1161
01:32:28.713 --> 01:32:30.797
No, I think ...

1162
01:32:31.465 --> 01:32:33.425
I think chairman.

1163
01:32:34.093 --> 01:32:35.510
What do you think?

1164
01:32:37.555 --> 01:32:40.140
- Chairman. That is interesting.
- Yeah.


1165
