1637
02:11:59.915 --> 02:12:05.002
I'd never forgive myself if I got you sick.
I don't wanna get you sick. I don't wanna --


1638
02:12:12.177 --> 02:12:14.011
Thank you.

1639
02:12:16.598 --> 02:12:18.349
Okay, Howard, I'm sitting.

1640
02:12:19.017 --> 02:12:22.103
I've brought along our accountings.
Now ...


1641
02:12:22.270 --> 02:12:25.439
... Pan Am is trading
at 13 and five-eighths.


1642
02:12:25.607 --> 02:12:28.234
TWA at four and a quarter.

1643
02:12:28.401 --> 02:12:29.860
- Now, if you take --
- Come on.


1644
02:12:30.028 --> 02:12:35.324
Come on, come on, come on.
We both know I'm not gonna sell TWA.


1645
02:12:35.492 --> 02:12:37.535
Besides, you couldn't afford her.

1646
02:12:37.702 --> 02:12:41.497
Our domestic routes alone
are worth more than twice Pan Am.


1647
02:12:42.082 --> 02:12:45.334
Well, considering our stock is trading
at three times yours ...


1648
02:12:45.502 --> 02:12:48.546
... I find that a dubious claim, Howard.

1649
02:12:48.713 --> 02:12:50.089
What I --

1650
02:12:52.217 --> 02:12:56.804
What I mean is,
you have no domestic routes. All right?


1651
02:12:56.972 --> 02:12:59.098
I mean, you get TWA,
you span the globe.


1652
02:12:59.266 --> 02:13:01.976
I'm not gonna sell,
and you know I'm not gonna sell.


1653
02:13:02.144 --> 02:13:04.019
Here's the point.

1654
02:13:04.187 --> 02:13:06.647
Owen Brewster works for you.

1655
02:13:07.232 --> 02:13:13.070
Howard, I didn't elect Senator Brewster.
We can thank the voters of Maine for that.


1656
02:13:20.745 --> 02:13:26.208
Now, if I appear at his hearings, Juan,
it could get nasty.


1657
02:13:26.376 --> 02:13:28.419
Real nasty for all of us.

1658
02:13:28.587 --> 02:13:32.923
Well, I think,
considerably more so for you.


1659
02:13:33.341 --> 02:13:36.552
While the good people of America
were losing sons at Anzio ...


1660
02:13:36.720 --> 02:13:40.431
... you produced a dirty movie
and built airplanes that don't fly.


1661
02:13:40.599 --> 02:13:43.184
Well, that's just not fair, is it?

1662
02:13:43.351 --> 02:13:47.146
I mean, the XF-11 flew quite well
for an hour and 45 minutes.


1663
02:13:47.314 --> 02:13:51.609
I wish you were up there with me, Juan.
It was exhilarating.


1664
02:13:52.569 --> 02:13:55.946
Be that as it may, you still have
to answer for the Spruce Goose.


1665
02:13:56.698 --> 02:13:59.158
It's called The Hercules!

1666
02:13:59.326 --> 02:14:02.578
And it will fly, goddamn it!

1667
02:14:02.746 --> 02:14:06.790
I hope so. The American people deserve
something for their $13 million.


1668
02:14:06.958 --> 02:14:09.960
I won't sell TWA!

1669
02:14:10.128 --> 02:14:11.295
I won't!

1670
02:14:16.301 --> 02:14:18.302
I know that, Howard.

1671
02:14:19.095 --> 02:14:20.804
I know that.

1672
02:14:22.599 --> 02:14:25.226
But I'm going to get it anyway.

1673
02:14:26.186 --> 02:14:30.064
You will default on your loan from
Equitable after Senator Brewster ...


1674
02:14:30.232 --> 02:14:34.526
... destroys your reputation and you can't
find additional capital for the airline.


1675
02:14:34.694 --> 02:14:39.907
The hearings will also show Hughes Aircraft
to be mismanaged and incompetent ...


1676
02:14:40.075 --> 02:14:42.159
... and it will go bankrupt too.

1677
02:14:42.327 --> 02:14:45.871
But you won't be insolvent.
You'll still have Tool Co.


1678
02:14:46.039 --> 02:14:49.875
Perhaps you'll head back to Houston
to rebuild your empire.


1679
02:14:50.126 --> 02:14:52.253
I rather hope you do.

1680
02:14:52.671 --> 02:14:56.006
By that time,
Pan Am will have bought TWA ...


1681
02:14:56.174 --> 02:15:00.219
... and painted all those magnificent
Connies blue and white.


1682
02:15:00.387 --> 02:15:05.266
So when you do return,
it will be on a Pan Am plane.


1683
02:15:08.687 --> 02:15:10.354
Well ...

1684
02:15:12.357 --> 02:15:15.442
You seem to have me
in a corner here, buddy.


1685
02:15:16.444 --> 02:15:19.613
Not a position in which
I'm very comfortable.


1686
02:15:21.199 --> 02:15:25.077
I think you're gonna be less comfortable
at Senator Brewster's hearings.


1687
02:15:26.204 --> 02:15:28.539
Very public, Howard.

1688
02:15:30.542 --> 02:15:33.961
Lots of cameras and newsmen.

1689
02:15:34.212 --> 02:15:37.965
I understand you're not
particularly fond of crowds.


1690
02:15:39.843 --> 02:15:43.012
Perhaps we should spare you that.

1691
02:15:44.889 --> 02:15:49.852
Well, thank you for your concern, Juan.

1692
02:15:50.020 --> 02:15:52.021
I find that ...

1693
02:15:53.148 --> 02:15:55.316
... very moving.

1694
02:15:56.067 --> 02:15:58.068
It's been a real pleasure.

1695
02:15:59.738 --> 02:16:02.823
Noah will see you back
to the airport now.


1696
02:16:03.825 --> 02:16:11.248
You fly safe.

1697
02:16:16.171 --> 02:16:18.922
Thank you, Howard,
and you take care of that cold.


1698
02:16:19.090 --> 02:16:21.008
Don't you worry.

1699
02:16:21.176 --> 02:16:23.344
I certainly will.

1700
02:16:24.262 --> 02:16:26.013
Bye-bye.

1701
02:16:30.685 --> 02:16:35.439
If you let him appear at those hearings,
the whole world will see what he's become.


1702
02:16:35.607 --> 02:16:38.525
People should remember him as he was.

1703
02:16:43.698 --> 02:16:47.201
He'll have a subpoena in three days
to appear in Washington.


1704
02:16:48.453 --> 02:16:51.038
If you can get him
out of there by then.

1705
02:17:40.839 --> 02:17:42.673
Mr. Hughes?

1706
02:17:48.763 --> 02:17:51.098
I don't have any shoes.

1707
02:17:52.934 --> 02:17:55.811
- Could you get me some shoes?
- Shoes.


1708
02:17:56.563 --> 02:17:58.105
Yeah.

1709
02:18:23.506 --> 02:18:26.133
How nice of you to dress for me.

1710
02:18:29.387 --> 02:18:31.513
Can I come in?

1711
02:18:32.307 --> 02:18:36.685
Yeah, you can come in.

1712
02:18:43.526 --> 02:18:45.486
Thank you for coming.

1713
02:18:57.916 --> 02:18:59.958
Now, let's get a drink.

1714
02:19:00.126 --> 02:19:04.254
Wait, wait, wait, honey.
You can't move. You're safe here.


1715
02:19:04.422 --> 02:19:07.549
You're in the germ-free zone now.
You understand?


1716
02:19:07.717 --> 02:19:13.180
- I'll take my chances.
- No, no, honey. Wait, wait.


1717
02:19:26.277 --> 02:19:28.695
Love what you've done with the place.

1718
02:19:35.495 --> 02:19:39.581
Now, let me look at you.

1719
02:19:44.295 --> 02:19:46.713
When do you go to Washington?

1720
02:19:47.215 --> 02:19:49.132
A week.

1721
02:19:49.300 --> 02:19:52.177
No, no. Just under a week.

1722
02:19:52.345 --> 02:19:56.807
I don't know the date today,
but I have to be ...


1723
02:19:56.975 --> 02:19:59.560
All right, take it easy.

1724
02:20:12.490 --> 02:20:15.158
There's nothing there, Howard.

1725
02:20:22.083 --> 02:20:25.502
I see things.

1726
02:20:26.337 --> 02:20:28.255
I know, baby.

1727
02:20:29.382 --> 02:20:31.758
Rinse your face off, now.

1728
02:20:40.685 --> 02:20:43.186
Put your hands in the water
and wash off the soap.


1729
02:20:43.354 --> 02:20:46.607
I'm right here. 
I'm not going anywhere.

1730
02:20:51.029 --> 02:20:54.489
- Does that look clean to you?
- Nothing's clean, Howard.


1731
02:20:54.657 --> 02:20:57.659
But we do our best, right?

1732
02:20:58.369 --> 02:21:00.120
Yeah.

1733
02:21:19.474 --> 02:21:21.183
What do you think?

1734
02:21:21.351 --> 02:21:24.770
- Well, I look all right.
- You look great.


1735
02:21:24.937 --> 02:21:26.605
Will you marry me?

1736
02:21:26.773 --> 02:21:29.483
You're too crazy for me.

1737
02:21:31.110 --> 02:21:33.487
I gotta go, baby.

1738
02:21:34.238 --> 02:21:36.073
Okay.

1739
02:21:36.783 --> 02:21:38.492
Thanks.

1740
02:21:44.415 --> 02:21:46.667
You'd do it for me.

1741
02:21:53.049 --> 02:21:55.008
Hi, Howard. How you doing?

1742
02:22:35.800 --> 02:22:38.135
The committee will come to order.

1743
02:22:38.803 --> 02:22:43.515
Ladies and gentlemen, I must insist that
we maintain quiet during these proceedings.


1744
02:22:43.683 --> 02:22:46.935
All right, Mr. Hughes,
will you stand and be sworn?


1745
02:22:48.896 --> 02:22:52.941
Do you solemnly swear that in the matter
now pending before this committee ...


1746
02:22:53.109 --> 02:22:57.237
... you will tell the whole truth
and nothing but the truth, so help you God?


1747
02:22:57.405 --> 02:22:59.656
- I do.
- Pardon me for speaking loudly ...


1748
02:22:59.824 --> 02:23:04.077
... but I know you have difficulty hearing.
- That's quite all right.


1749
02:23:04.370 --> 02:23:07.956
I mean, everybody knows I'm deaf.
I'm not gonna try to hide it.


1750
02:23:10.334 --> 02:23:13.003
Mr. Hughes, it is the intention
of this committee --


1751
02:23:13.171 --> 02:23:14.755
Mr. Hughes has a statement.

1752
02:23:16.090 --> 02:23:22.012
All right, you may proceed
with this statement, Mr. Hughes.


1753
02:23:28.311 --> 02:23:30.604
Mr. Hughes, do you have a statement?

1754
02:23:37.945 --> 02:23:42.199
I'm gonna attempt to be honest here.

1755
02:23:42.950 --> 02:23:47.954
I mean, my reputation's being destroyed,
so I might as well lay the cards on the table.


1756
02:23:48.790 --> 02:23:52.876
Senator Brewster, if you hadn't
gone too far overboard ...


1757
02:23:53.044 --> 02:23:55.712
... if you hadn't put
the red-hot iron in my side ...


1758
02:23:55.880 --> 02:24:00.383
... I might have been willing to take a
shellacking in this publicity spree of yours.


1759
02:24:00.551 --> 02:24:06.139
I may have been willing to sit back and take
a certain amount of abuse simply because ...


1760
02:24:06.891 --> 02:24:09.476
... well, I am only a private citizen.

1761
02:24:09.644 --> 02:24:11.728
Whereas you are a senator ...

1762
02:24:11.896 --> 02:24:14.815
... with all sorts of powers.

1763
02:24:15.650 --> 02:24:18.568
But I think this goddamn circus
has gone on long enough!


1764
02:24:18.736 --> 02:24:22.614
- That's quite sufficient.
- You have called me a liar, sir, in the press.


1765
02:24:22.782 --> 02:24:25.826
You have called me a liar
and a thief and a war profiteer!


1766
02:24:25.993 --> 02:24:29.955
- The witness will restrain --
- Why not tell the truth for once, senator?


1767
02:24:30.122 --> 02:24:34.584
Why not tell the truth that this investigation
was really born on the day that TWA ...


1768
02:24:34.752 --> 02:24:40.340
... decided to fly to Europe? On the day that
TWA first invaded Juan Trippe's territory!


1769
02:24:40.508 --> 02:24:43.051
- Sit down.
- On the day TWA first challenged ...


1770
02:24:43.219 --> 02:24:47.764
... the generally accepted theory that only
Juan Trippe's great Pan American Airways ...


1771
02:24:47.932 --> 02:24:52.060
... had the right to fly the Atlantic!
- You are not here to make a speech.


1772
02:24:53.062 --> 02:24:56.523
I asked for silence!
I asked for quiet in this room ...


1773
02:24:56.691 --> 02:25:00.735
We have in our possession receipts
in the amount of $170,000 ...


1774
02:25:02.071 --> 02:25:06.366
... acquired from Mr. John Meyer.
Mr. Meyer works for you, does he not?


1775
02:25:06.534 --> 02:25:10.704
- He does.
- And what is his official title?


1776
02:25:11.622 --> 02:25:15.166
I don't exactly know, senator.
A lot of people work for me.


1777
02:25:15.334 --> 02:25:18.128
Can you explain why your press agent
would pay out ...


1778
02:25:18.296 --> 02:25:23.300
... more than $170,000 to representatives
of the United States Air Force?


1779
02:25:23.467 --> 02:25:27.929
- I don't know. You'd have to ask him.
- Well, would you produce him?


1780
02:25:28.806 --> 02:25:31.975
- Produce him?
- Will you cause him to appear?


1781
02:25:32.143 --> 02:25:35.395
You had John Meyer on the stand
for three days last week.


1782
02:25:35.563 --> 02:25:38.315
Be that as it may,
we would like him to reappear.


1783
02:25:38.482 --> 02:25:41.985
Would you ask him to return?

1784
02:25:47.992 --> 02:25:50.243
No, I don't think I will.

1785
02:25:51.871 --> 02:25:55.081
Will you try to have him return?

1786
02:25:57.168 --> 02:26:01.630
- No, I don't think I'll try.
- You don't think you'll try?


1787
02:26:02.673 --> 02:26:05.675
No, I don't think so.

1788
02:26:05.843 --> 02:26:10.680
The $170,000 paid out to the Air Force
in the form of hotel suites ...


1789
02:26:10.848 --> 02:26:12.474
... TWA stock ...

1790
02:26:13.142 --> 02:26:15.602
... female companionship.

1791
02:26:15.811 --> 02:26:20.106
Now, is it possible that
these could be considered bribes?


1792
02:26:20.775 --> 02:26:23.109
I suppose you could call them that, yes.

1793
02:26:24.487 --> 02:26:25.862
Would you repeat that?

1794
02:26:26.822 --> 02:26:30.659
I said, I suppose you could
consider them bribes, yes.


1795
02:26:33.287 --> 02:26:36.122
Well, would you like
to explain that, Mr. Hughes?


1796
02:26:37.833 --> 02:26:42.045
I'm afraid you don't know how
the aviation business works, senator.


1797
02:26:42.213 --> 02:26:46.633
See, wining and dining Air Force dignitaries
is common in our business.


1798
02:26:46.801 --> 02:26:51.721
It's because we all want the big contracts.
All the major aircraft companies do it.


1799
02:26:51.889 --> 02:26:54.057
I don't know whether
it's a good system ...


1800
02:26:54.225 --> 02:26:58.478
... I just know it's not illegal.
You, senator, you are the lawmaker.


1801
02:26:58.646 --> 02:27:03.233
If you pass a law that states no one
can entertain Air Force officers, well, hell ...


1802
02:27:03.401 --> 02:27:05.568
... I'd be happy to abide by it.

1803
02:27:07.655 --> 02:27:11.074
Your story is a pack of lies. I can
tear it apart if allowed to cross-examine.


1804
02:27:12.410 --> 02:27:16.705
- We're not gonna have this bickering.
- Yes. Somewhere between two and 500 ...


1805
02:27:16.872 --> 02:27:20.750
... if you'll let me get started.
- If you believe your wealth and power ...


1806
02:27:20.918 --> 02:27:24.879
... can intimidate any member
of this committee, you're mistaken.


1807
02:27:25.047 --> 02:27:27.924
- Now submit your questions.
- I'll put this very simply.


1808
02:27:28.092 --> 02:27:31.136
On February 12th,
at the Mayflower Hotel ...


1809
02:27:31.303 --> 02:27:36.933
... did you or did you not tell me
that if I were to sell TWA to Pan Am ...


1810
02:27:37.101 --> 02:27:39.894
... that this entire investigation
would be called off?


1811
02:27:40.062 --> 02:27:43.773
I did not. And I have asked you
to submit your questions in writing.


1812
02:27:43.941 --> 02:27:47.902
- How long have you known Juan Trippe?
- I've known him for some time now.


1813
02:27:48.070 --> 02:27:52.782
- And that's not the question.
- Is it not true that Juan donated $20,000 ...


1814
02:27:52.950 --> 02:27:57.203
... to your last campaign? I mean,
he spoke to me as if you worked for him.


1815
02:28:01.250 --> 02:28:03.126
I have a personal friendship with --

1816
02:28:03.294 --> 02:28:06.713
Is it true you accept free Pan Am tickets
to circle the globe ...


1817
02:28:06.881 --> 02:28:09.799
... in support of your C.A.B. bill?
- No, it is not true.


1818
02:28:09.967 --> 02:28:14.179
Well, who wrote that bill, senator?
Who actually wrote the C.A.B. bill?


1819
02:28:14.346 --> 02:28:18.308
- The actual words. Did you write them?
- This is not how these hearings ...


1820
02:28:18.476 --> 02:28:22.562
... are gonna be conducted.
- I have it. Maybe it'll refresh your memory.


1821
02:28:22.730 --> 02:28:27.317
"Bill S-987 to amend
the Civil Aeronautics Act."


1822
02:28:27.485 --> 02:28:30.320
Now, you introduced this bill
to the Senate.


1823
02:28:32.782 --> 02:28:34.908
A lot of words.

1824
02:28:35.242 --> 02:28:37.243
You write all of them?

1825
02:28:37.828 --> 02:28:40.705
- Did you write any of them, senator?
- Now, look --


1826
02:28:40.873 --> 02:28:43.875
Now, this entire bill was written
by Pan Am executives ...


1827
02:28:44.043 --> 02:28:48.338
... and designed to give that airline
a monopoly on international travel.


1828
02:28:48.506 --> 02:28:52.967
You've been flogging this bill all around
the world on their behalf, have you not?


1829
02:28:53.135 --> 02:28:56.888
I have duties that take me
all over the world, Mr. Hughes.


1830
02:28:57.056 --> 02:29:02.102
Well, what the hell does a senator
from Maine need to visit Peru for?


1831
02:29:02.853 --> 02:29:07.524
I was seeking outlets for our trade goods.

1832
02:29:08.484 --> 02:29:11.444
Buy a lot of
lobsters down there, do they?

1833
02:29:14.031 --> 02:29:17.826
Senator, how many times have you visited
Trippe's office in New York ...


1834
02:29:17.993 --> 02:29:20.370
... in the last three months?

1835
02:29:22.957 --> 02:29:25.708
Would you like me to tell you, senator?

1836
02:29:26.460 --> 02:29:29.921
All right, this has gone on long enough.
Juan is a great American.


1837
02:29:30.089 --> 02:29:34.467
His airline has advanced the cause
of commercial aviation for decades.


1838
02:29:34.635 --> 02:29:40.181
Juan Trippe is a patriot. Juan Trippe is not
a man who is interested in making money.


1839
02:29:41.058 --> 02:29:44.853
Well, I'm sure his stockholders
would be happy to hear that.


1840
02:29:46.522 --> 02:29:48.022
We're gonna clear this room.

1841
02:29:48.566 --> 02:29:53.361
This is James McNamara speaking to you
from the Hughes 2000-ton flying boat ...


1842
02:29:53.529 --> 02:29:56.698
... the world's largest aircraft.
This is the sky giant ...


1843
02:29:56.866 --> 02:30:00.952
... which has prompted Congress to
investigate the war contracts of Mr. Hughes.


1844
02:30:01.120 --> 02:30:04.706
Before boarding the craft,
Mr. Hughes told newsmen that this test ...


1845
02:30:04.874 --> 02:30:09.085
... would be solely a taxi experiment.
He said he didn't know what might happen.


1846
02:30:09.253 --> 02:30:11.129
The mammoth flying plywood shell ...

1847
02:30:13.215 --> 02:30:16.968
... might ship water under high-speed
taxi pressure. He will not take ...


1848
02:30:17.136 --> 02:30:20.430
... the craft into the air until next spring.
The thin man from Culver City ...


1849
02:30:20.598 --> 02:30:25.101
... pronounced the craft an unknown
quantity. He has an idea what it can do ...


1850
02:30:25.269 --> 02:30:27.270
None of that, now. None of that.

1851
02:30:27.438 --> 02:30:30.356
We are about 5 feet
in back of Mr. Hughes.


1852
02:30:30.524 --> 02:30:33.902
We are looking through
one of the side windows in the cockpit.


1853
02:30:34.069 --> 02:30:36.613
Professor, why don't you
come on up front here.


1854
02:30:37.031 --> 02:30:40.283
In other words, we are 30 feet high
in this aircraft.


1855
02:30:40.451 --> 02:30:45.079
Strap yourself in right there.
You ought to be able to see just great.


1856
02:30:46.081 --> 02:30:49.334
Huge crowds jam the surrounding
shoreline this morning.


1857
02:30:49.501 --> 02:30:52.712
All right, boys, let's fire it up.

1858
02:30:56.592 --> 02:30:57.967
One's good.

1859
02:30:59.220 --> 02:31:01.179
Two's good.

1860
02:31:01.347 --> 02:31:03.056
Three's good.

1861
02:31:03.224 --> 02:31:05.266
Four's good.

1862
02:31:05.434 --> 02:31:07.143
Five's good.

1863
02:31:07.311 --> 02:31:08.811
Six is good.

1864
02:31:08.979 --> 02:31:10.313
Seven's good.

1865
02:31:10.481 --> 02:31:12.398
Eight's good.

1866
02:31:13.484 --> 02:31:17.320
- Advancing master throttles.
- Advancing master throttles.


1867
02:31:18.948 --> 02:31:21.658
As you probably know,
I have to do a great deal ...


1868
02:31:21.825 --> 02:31:23.952
... of screaming into our microphone.

1869
02:31:24.119 --> 02:31:28.498
- Understood. Lower it 15 degrees of flaps.
- Lowering 15 degrees of flaps.


1870
02:31:29.166 --> 02:31:32.919
Howard, she's gotta hit 70
to have any kind of chance.


1871
02:31:33.087 --> 02:31:35.338
Yeah, I know. I know.

1872
02:31:35.506 --> 02:31:39.842
It's a beautiful day here off the coast
of Southern California. Blue skies ...


1873
02:31:40.010 --> 02:31:43.513
... a warm sun ...
- Twenty-five miles per hour.


1874
02:31:43.681 --> 02:31:45.932
- And a relatively calm sea ...
- Thirty.


1875
02:31:47.559 --> 02:31:48.851
Thirty-five.

1876
02:31:49.019 --> 02:31:52.981
One would think these eight power plants
might shake the craft to pieces ...


1877
02:31:53.357 --> 02:31:54.941
Take it easy, Howard.

1878
02:31:57.236 --> 02:32:01.030
- Forty!
- Throttling back for starboard turn 180.


1879
02:32:01.198 --> 02:32:03.533
Throttling back for starboard turn 180.

1880
02:32:08.789 --> 02:32:11.291
The flight crew itself
consists of four men.


1881
02:32:11.458 --> 02:32:15.503
Mr. Hughes, however, has added 11
maintenance men to this maiden taxi test ...


1882
02:32:15.671 --> 02:32:21.301
... stationed at various places throughout the
ship, checking points of stress and strain.


1883
02:32:23.721 --> 02:32:25.388
How does she sound, Odie?

1884
02:32:26.307 --> 02:32:28.308
Sounds good, Howard.

1885
02:32:31.603 --> 02:32:33.730
- Professor.
- Yes?


1886
02:32:33.897 --> 02:32:35.815
Would you do me a favor?

1887
02:32:36.275 --> 02:32:40.320
Would you take a look out that window
and tell me what the wind is doing?


1888
02:32:45.367 --> 02:32:49.704
I would say that
we have a 15-knot wind.

1889
02:32:49.872 --> 02:32:53.249
Would you call that a headwind,
professor?


1890
02:32:53.959 --> 02:32:56.169
I would, Mr. Hughes.

1891
02:32:56.337 --> 02:32:59.922
We must maintain silence. We must
have quiet during the proceedings.


1892
02:33:00.090 --> 02:33:02.425
Mr. Hughes, will you stand and be sworn?

1893
02:33:02.593 --> 02:33:05.053
Mr. Hughes, did you receive ...

1894
02:33:05.220 --> 02:33:11.601
... $43 million to manufacture 100 XF-11
spy planes for the United States Air Force?


1895
02:33:12.853 --> 02:33:14.020
I did.

1896
02:33:14.313 --> 02:33:18.441
How many functional planes did you
deliver to the United States Air Force?


1897
02:33:18.776 --> 02:33:19.776
None.

1898
02:33:19.943 --> 02:33:23.196
Would you lean a little closer
to the microphones, sir?


1899
02:33:23.697 --> 02:33:24.864
None.

1900
02:33:25.032 --> 02:33:28.951
Did you receive $13 million
to manufacture ...


1901
02:33:29.119 --> 02:33:33.915
... a prototype of a flying boat
known as The Hercules?


1902
02:33:35.459 --> 02:33:36.751
I did.

1903
02:33:36.919 --> 02:33:39.504
And did you deliver that plane?

1904
02:33:39.797 --> 02:33:41.089
I did not.

1905
02:33:42.174 --> 02:33:45.468
So by your admission
in this chamber, Mr. Hughes ...


1906
02:33:45.636 --> 02:33:48.554
... you have received $56 million ...

1907
02:33:48.931 --> 02:33:53.142
... from the United States government
for planes you never delivered.


1908
02:33:53.977 --> 02:33:55.770
That is correct.

1909
02:33:58.190 --> 02:34:01.192
Well, excuse me for asking,
Mr. Hughes ...


1910
02:34:01.360 --> 02:34:03.319
... but where did all that money go?

1911
02:34:03.695 --> 02:34:08.241
Well, it went into the planes, senator.
And a lot more.


1912
02:34:08.409 --> 02:34:13.204
More? Do tell, Mr. Hughes,
what other larcenies did you commit?


1913
02:34:13.414 --> 02:34:18.668
I mean, I put my money
into the planes, senator. My money.


1914
02:34:21.171 --> 02:34:25.716
- See, the thing is that I care --
- Your personal finances are not --


1915
02:34:25.884 --> 02:34:28.594
Let him speak.

1916
02:34:31.932 --> 02:34:33.266
Proceed, Mr. Hughes.

1917
02:34:35.352 --> 02:34:40.690
See, the thing is,
I care very much about aviation.


1918
02:34:40.941 --> 02:34:45.611
It has been the great joy of my life. That's
why I put my own money into these planes.


1919
02:34:45.779 --> 02:34:50.199
And I've lost millions, senator,
and I'll go on losing millions. It's just ...


1920
02:34:50.367 --> 02:34:52.285
... what I do.

1921
02:34:52.619 --> 02:34:56.956
Now, if I've lost a lot of the government's
money during the war, I hope folks ...


1922
02:34:57.124 --> 02:34:59.709
... will put that into perspective.

1923
02:34:59.877 --> 02:35:03.212
More than 60 other airplanes ordered
from such firms as ...


1924
02:35:03.380 --> 02:35:07.383
... Lockheed, Douglas, Northrop and Boeing
never saw action either.


1925
02:35:07.551 --> 02:35:14.056
In all, more than $800 million was spent
during the war on planes that never flew.


1926
02:35:14.224 --> 02:35:19.353
Over 6 billion on other weapons
that were never delivered.


1927
02:35:19.521 --> 02:35:23.983
Yet Hughes Aircraft, with her 56 million ...

1928
02:35:24.151 --> 02:35:26.652
... is the only firm
under investigation here.


1929
02:35:26.820 --> 02:35:32.408
I cannot help but think that has a little more
to do with TWA than planes that did not fly.


1930
02:35:32.576 --> 02:35:36.537
- You've made your point, Mr. Hughes.
- One second. I have one more thing ...


1931
02:35:36.914 --> 02:35:39.165
... to say here to this committee.

1932
02:35:39.333 --> 02:35:41.876
And that has to do with The Hercules.

1933
02:35:42.503 --> 02:35:47.757
Now, I am supposed to be many things
which are not complimentary.


1934
02:35:47.925 --> 02:35:49.967
I am supposed to be capricious.

1935
02:35:50.135 --> 02:35:54.096
I have been called a playboy.
I've even been called an eccentric ...


1936
02:35:54.264 --> 02:35:58.518
... but I do not believe that I have
the reputation of being a liar.


1937
02:35:59.478 --> 02:36:02.855
Needless to say, The Hercules
was a monumental undertaking.


1938
02:36:03.023 --> 02:36:05.733
It is the largest plane ever built.

1939
02:36:05.901 --> 02:36:09.779
It is over five stories tall with a wingspan
longer than a football field.


1940
02:36:09.947 --> 02:36:11.781
That's more than a city block.

1941
02:36:11.949 --> 02:36:16.494
Now, I put the sweat of my life into this.
I got my reputation all rolled up in it.


1942
02:36:16.662 --> 02:36:20.122
I have stated several times
that if The Hercules fails to fly ...


1943
02:36:20.290 --> 02:36:24.418
... I will leave this country
and never come back. And I mean it.


1944
02:36:25.796 --> 02:36:29.632
Now, Senator Brewster,
you can subpoena me ...


1945
02:36:29.800 --> 02:36:34.637
... you can arrest me, you can even claim
I've folded up and taken a run-out powder ...


1946
02:36:34.805 --> 02:36:39.809
... but, well, I've had just about enough
of this nonsense. Good afternoon.


1947
02:36:40.227 --> 02:36:41.477
I had to do it.

1948
02:36:41.645 --> 02:36:45.606
- Mr. Hughes.
- Mr. Hughes.


1949
02:36:45.774 --> 02:36:48.317
I'd love to see
The Hercules in the air.

1950
02:36:48.485 --> 02:36:50.903
Thank you, thank you so much.

1951
02:36:59.913 --> 02:37:00.997
Switch it off.

1952
02:37:01.164 --> 02:37:04.000
- The hearings aren't over yet.
- The hearings are over.


1953
02:37:06.712 --> 02:37:09.547
The airline bill will be defeated
in the Senate.


1954
02:37:09.715 --> 02:37:12.800
TWA will begin flights from
New York to Paris ...


1955
02:37:12.968 --> 02:37:18.764
... then on to Moscow, to Japan,
to Hawaii, to Los Angeles ...


1956
02:37:20.892 --> 02:37:22.935
... to New York.

1957
02:37:26.773 --> 02:37:28.441
Fuck.

1958
02:37:32.487 --> 02:37:36.324
- Power coming up.
- Power coming up.


1959
02:37:39.620 --> 02:37:41.871
Howard Hughes has just alerted us.

1960
02:37:42.039 --> 02:37:46.626
He has asked everyone to hold on.
Tremendous horsepower kicking up.


1961
02:37:48.211 --> 02:37:49.337
Let me hear it, Odie.

1962
02:37:49.504 --> 02:37:51.547
Twenty-five miles per hour.

1963
02:37:52.132 --> 02:37:53.382
Thirty.

1964
02:37:53.717 --> 02:37:55.926
Here we go. Here we go.

1965
02:37:56.094 --> 02:37:58.262
- Thirty-five.
- The air-speed indicator ...


1966
02:37:58.430 --> 02:38:02.058
... has moved up to 25. Thirty.

1967
02:38:02.476 --> 02:38:04.560
- Thirty-five.
- Forty.


1968
02:38:04.728 --> 02:38:06.562
As he pushes the throttle it's 40.

1969
02:38:06.730 --> 02:38:10.024
- Forty-five.
- Forty-five. More throttle.


1970
02:38:10.192 --> 02:38:12.193
- Forty-five.
- Fifty.


1971
02:38:12.778 --> 02:38:15.237
- It's 50 over a choppy sea.
- Fifty-five.


1972
02:38:15.405 --> 02:38:17.740
It's 55. It's 55.

1973
02:38:18.241 --> 02:38:20.409
- Sixty.
- More throttle. It's 60.


1974
02:38:20.577 --> 02:38:22.328
- Sixty-five.
- Sixty-five.


1975
02:38:27.000 --> 02:38:28.918
- Seventy.
- It's 70.


1976
02:38:29.086 --> 02:38:31.837
- Seventy-five.
- It's 75.


1977
02:38:39.221 --> 02:38:44.517
And something momentarily cuts out.
I believe we are airborne.


1978
02:38:44.685 --> 02:38:48.270
We are airborne, ladies and gentlemen.
I don't believe that Hughes ...


1979
02:38:48.438 --> 02:38:51.190
... meant this to be. I don't know.

1980
02:38:53.402 --> 02:38:58.781
And we were really up in the air.
We were really up in the air.


1981
02:39:03.203 --> 02:39:06.622
Ladies and gentlemen,
the Hughes mammoth aircraft ...


1982
02:39:06.790 --> 02:39:11.293
... has flown this afternoon
in Los Angeles Harbor.


1983
02:39:11.461 --> 02:39:15.673
Well, it certainly looks at this moment
that Howard Hughes will be around ...


1984
02:39:15.841 --> 02:39:19.719
... the United States for quite
some time to come.


1985
02:39:30.772 --> 02:39:34.817
We must understand that technologies
like these are the way of the future.


1986
02:39:34.985 --> 02:39:38.529
- That's enough questions.
- TWA and Hughes Aircraft are delighted ...


1987
02:39:38.697 --> 02:39:41.991
... to have you come here
and witness this wonderful sight.


1988
02:39:42.159 --> 02:39:44.326
- Excuse us for just a second.
- All right.


1989
02:39:44.494 --> 02:39:46.495
- So you feel like going to Paris?
- Now?


1990
02:39:46.663 --> 02:39:48.664
TWA is starting up flights to Europe.

1991
02:39:48.832 --> 02:39:52.293
I thought I might pilot the first one.
Ought to be some fun.


1992
02:39:52.461 --> 02:39:55.171
- Lots of shopping in Paris.
- I'll buy you anything.


1993
02:39:55.338 --> 02:39:58.257
You can buy me dinner. 
How about that?

1994
02:40:00.510 --> 02:40:02.928
Dinner, then. We got a date?

1995
02:40:03.138 --> 02:40:05.473
Okay, baby, you got a date.

1996
02:40:07.100 --> 02:40:10.895
I'll be back in a second,
but don't you go anywhere, now. I mean it.


1997
02:40:11.062 --> 02:40:14.064
All right, listen, boys.
Something new. Jet airplanes.


1998
02:40:14.232 --> 02:40:17.193
- You know about jets?
- No, but it sounds expensive.


1999
02:40:17.360 --> 02:40:19.779
Oh, it will be,
but we gotta get started.

2000
02:40:21.031 --> 02:40:23.824
Come on, walk with me.

2001
02:40:23.992 --> 02:40:26.327
Whoever can start utilizing
jet technology ...


2002
02:40:26.495 --> 02:40:30.372
... on commercial airliners is gonna win.
What do you know about the science?


2003
02:40:30.540 --> 02:40:35.002
I know a little. I can work something
to show you. Basic turbine stuff.


2004
02:40:39.633 --> 02:40:43.469
Noah, who are those fellas?

2005
02:40:44.387 --> 02:40:46.180
Do they work for me?

2006
02:40:47.516 --> 02:40:49.809
Everybody works for you, Howard.

2007
02:40:56.566 --> 02:41:01.278
Lockheed worked on the F-80. Let's get
Bob Gross and see if he can help us out.


2008
02:41:01.446 --> 02:41:03.739
- What, now?
- Of course now.


2009
02:41:03.907 --> 02:41:06.867
We gotta get into it.
Jets are the way of the future.


2010
02:41:07.035 --> 02:41:10.246
- It's 4:30.
- I talked to Bob last week. He's in New York.


2011
02:41:10.413 --> 02:41:13.040
- So it's 7:30.
- He won't be in the office.


2012
02:41:13.208 --> 02:41:16.418
We'll figure out what hotel he's at.
Do you want a call ...


2013
02:41:16.586 --> 02:41:20.089
... or you want some kind of meeting?
- We want a meeting, don't we?


2014
02:41:20.257 --> 02:41:23.509
Do you want me bring him
out here tomorrow, then, Howard?


2015
02:41:24.511 --> 02:41:26.929
- The way of the future.
- Howard?


2016
02:41:27.097 --> 02:41:28.848
- Howard?
- The way of the future.


2017
02:41:30.350 --> 02:41:33.102
- The way of the future.
- Let's take a walk, Howard.


2018
02:41:33.270 --> 02:41:35.187
- Way of the future.
- Give me a hand.


2019
02:41:35.355 --> 02:41:45.355
The way of the future.
The way of the future.


2020
02:41:52.122 --> 02:41:56.083
All right, stay here. I'll be right back.
You understand, Howard?


2021
02:41:56.251 --> 02:41:58.002
The way of the future.

2022
02:41:58.169 --> 02:42:01.797
Guard the door. I'll get a doctor.
No one sees him like this.


2023
02:42:01.965 --> 02:42:10.139
The way of the future.
The way of the future.


2024
02:42:14.269 --> 02:42:16.061
The way of the future.

2025
02:42:22.319 --> 02:42:24.361
You are not safe.

2026
02:42:32.871 --> 02:42:34.121
When I grow up ...

2027
02:42:34.664 --> 02:42:37.666
... I'm gonna fly the fastest planes
ever built ...


2028
02:42:37.834 --> 02:42:40.419
... make the biggest movies ever ...

2029
02:42:40.587 --> 02:42:43.505
... and be the
richest man in the world.

2030
02:42:56.770 --> 02:43:06.770
The way of the future.